turns: Hillary Clinton's security detail added a second identical Scooby van to her motorcade during a campaign stop in Iowa, possibly for security reasons or to confuse potential attackers. The two vans, one Chevy and one GMC, were seen taking up positions in the Clinton convoy together. The use of decoy vehicles is not uncommon for the Secret Service, which often employs similar tactics with Marine One helicopters and other vehicles used by VIPs. The addition of the second Scooby van appears to be part of an ongoing security strategy to protect Clinton, a former first lady and secretary of state, while she campaigns for the Democratic presidential nomination.

A Georgia mother of six, Kalimah Dixon, is seeking help after a fire destroyed her family's rented condo, leaving them homeless and with nothing. The fire occurred early Monday morning, and fortunately, Dixon was able to safely evacuate her children, aged one to 14. However, she is now facing challenges in finding a new home as she is currently unemployed and was attending school full-time. She has created a GoFundMe page with a current total of $4,619 in donations, and is asking for assistance as her family has nowhere to go.

An Australian couple abandoned their baby boy born through a surrogacy deal in India, leaving him stateless, despite repeated warnings from government officials. The couple, from New South Wales, where international surrogacy arrangements are illegal, traveled to India in late 2012 and sought citizenship for a baby girl, planning to leave her twin brother behind due to financial reasons. They told consular staff they wanted a baby girl to "complete their family." The couple was warned that the boy would be left stateless in India if they proceeded with their plan, as India does not recognize surrogate children as citizens. Documents obtained by ABC reveal the shocking details of the case and raise concerns about the legality and ethics of international surrogacy arrangements.

Kecil, a baby orangutan, had a difficult start to life after being rejected by his natural mother and a surrogate mother. However, he found love and care with Maggie, an experienced orangutan mother, at Chicago's Brookfield Zoo. Maggie has been raising Kecil for the past 10 months, and the two have a strong bond.

Kecil's journey began at Toledo Zoo, where he was moved after his natural mother failed to bond with him. He was then placed with a second surrogate at Milwaukee County Zoo, but she did not bond with him either. Maggie, the oldest orangutan in North America, took on the role of Kecil's surrogate mother and has been caring for him since.

Zookeepers were initially worried that Maggie might reject Kecil, but the pair immediately showed signs of intimacy. A turning point came when a fire alarm sounded at the zoo, frightening Kecil. He ran to Maggie for comfort, showing a strong bond between them.

Now, Kecil is ready for his first public appearance at the Brookfield Zoo's Tropic World Asia enclosure. He will be on display on Saturday and Sunday between 10 am and midday, and will eventually join the zoo's other four orangutans in an exhibit. For now, Kecil and Maggie are living in isolation, similar to their natural habitat.

Paris Saint-Germain star Javier Pastore has responded to Eric Cantona's claim that he is the greatest footballer on the planet by saying that Lionel Messi and Cristiano Ronaldo are a class above him. Despite Cantona's praise, Pastore believes the Barcelona and Juventus superstars are exceptional players. Pastore and his teammates traveled to the Nou Camp for their second-leg tie against Barcelona in the Champions League. Pastore scored a brace in PSG's 3-1 win against Nice on Saturday, helping the team regain the top spot in Ligue 1.

Amanda Burleigh, a midwife, has successfully campaigned for a change in the medical practice of immediate cord-clamping after birth. The practice, introduced in the 1950s, was believed to reduce the risk of maternal hemorrhage but was never grounded in evidence. With the help of Dr. David Hutchon, an obstetrician, and other medical professionals, they gathered evidence showing that immediate cord-clamping could be harmful, particularly for premature babies.

The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) has revised its guidelines, advising doctors and midwives not to routinely clamp the cord earlier than one minute after birth, and to leave it intact for up to five minutes if the mother requests. This change will not only improve medical outcomes but also allow mothers more time to bond with their newborns.

French President Francois Hollande has vowed to "show no mercy" if French peacekeepers in the Central African Republic are found guilty of raping hungry children in exchange for food. The French defense ministry has denied covering up the scandal, claiming to have launched an investigation immediately after receiving a leaked UN report on the subject in July 2015. The alleged abuse took place between December 2013 and June 2014 at a center for displaced people near Bangui airport, and involved 14 soldiers deployed to restore order after a 2013 coup. A UN employee, Anders Kompass, is accused of leaking the report and has since been suspended. The Central African Republic has yet to officially react to the allegations, but a government member called the alleged actions "horrible and unacceptable."

A shocking ceremony attempting to resurrect a dead two-year-old boy was caught on camera at a Texas church. The child, identified as Benjamin, was held by Texas pastor's wife Aracely Meza as others, including a man believed to be her husband Pastor Daniel Meza, gathered around. The witness, who knew the child's mother since she was pregnant, said the child was possessed by demons, according to pastors.

Aracely Meza, who is reportedly not the child's mother, was arrested on Monday and has been charged with injury to a child by omission. In the video, she uses oils and prays while trying to bring the child back to life, invoking Jesus during the 'rising ceremony.' The ceremony took place at a home that also operated as a church, with services presided by Daniel and Aracely Meza.

The child's death is reported to have taken place on March 22, and police found out about the ceremony on March 26 when they received an anonymous tip. The child's parents took the body to Mexico the following day, and police are now investigating. Two phone numbers for the home were disconnected, and a witness claimed that five children under the age of ten, both boys and girls, were living at the home and had been taken away by Child Protective Services.

John Higgins and Graeme Dott, both from Scotland, had a successful day at the Betfred World Championship, with Higgins winning 10-5 against Robert Milkins and Dott winning 10-8 against Ricky Walden. Higgins showcased impressive form, and with his recent Welsh Open title, he's dreaming of a fifth world championship. Dott, a former champion, also played well and defeated Walden. Both Scottish players are looking forward to the possibility of winning the world title.

Barcelona stars Neymar, Dani Alves, and Adriano looked delighted after their victory over Celta Vigo in La Liga, despite their questionable choice of matching denim outfits. The Brazilians played crucial roles in the hard-fought win, which was secured by Jeremy Mathieu's winning goal. Mathieu admitted that Barcelona had a poor performance, attributing it to the international break, but praised his defensive partner Pique for his impressive display. The three Brazilian players all started for Barcelona and played a critical part in the win, which helped the team regain the top spot in La Liga.

Chelsea manager Jose Mourinho is planning to make a summer transfer bid for Atletico Madrid midfielder Koke. The club's technical director, Michael Emenalo, recently traveled to Spain to watch Koke during Atletico's win against Deportivo. According to Spanish newspaper AS, Mourinho may offer second-choice left-back Filipe Luis as part of the deal. Koke, an Atletico academy graduate, has a release clause of around £50 million, which Chelsea appears willing to pay. The 23-year-old has been a key player for Atletico, helping them reach the Champions League final last season.

Tom Ballard, a renowned climber, plans to climb K2, 20 years after his mother, Alison Hargreaves, died descending from its peak. Ballard, who was six at the time of his mother's death, has grown up with a passion for climbing. Last month, he became the first to solo climb all six of the great north faces of the Alps in the winter season. He is now training for K2, a mountain that is more difficult to reach than Mount Everest and has claimed the lives of many climbers. Ballard's mother was a celebrated climber who was only the second person to climb Everest without sherpas or bottled oxygen. She was known for pursuing her climbing career while raising a family, despite facing criticism for doing so. Her death in 1995 on the descent from K2 left a lasting impact on her family, and now, 20 years later, Tom Ballard is determined to follow in her footsteps and conquer K2.

A consortium called UK Oil & Gas Investments claims to have discovered up to 100 billion barrels of oil beneath the Home Counties in an area called "Britain’s Dallas." The oil is reportedly located in the Weald Basin, which spans across Surrey, Sussex, Hampshire, and Kent. The consortium believes the oil reserves could meet up to a third of Britain's oil demand within 15 years, reducing reliance on oil from the Middle East and Russia.

However, industry experts are skeptical about the claims, calling them "overly optimistic." They argue that only a fraction of the oil may be accessible for extraction, and that fracking might be required to retrieve significant volumes. The site at Horse Hill, where the discovery was made, has been described as "world-class" and could potentially produce a significant portion of Britain's oil demand in the future.

Notably, the British government owns the land under private properties, meaning homeowners would not receive any profit from the oil found beneath their homes. Oil companies must pay the government for an annual license to excavate oil and keep the profits, while the government also gains tax revenue from the oil extracted. To gain permission to drill or frack, companies must consult communities and obtain planning permission from local councils.

The British Veterinary Association has withdrawn its support for the controversial shooting of free-running badgers in pilot culls, saying the first two years did not prove the method's effectiveness and humane nature. They still support badger culling to tackle tuberculosis in cattle and propose completing the pilot culls by trapping and shooting badgers in cages. Animal welfare campaigners welcome the news but find ongoing support for cage-trapping and shooting regrettable. The Environment Secretary, Liz Truss, has promised to roll out more culls across the country if the Tories win the election. Her comments come as the incidence of TB has decreased on farms in pilot areas where culling of badgers has taken place over the last two years. The government's strategy also includes cattle movement controls, vaccination in 'edge' areas around disease hotspots, and culling where the disease is rife.

Modern technology, while intended to make life easier, often creates more problems in relationships. Today's connected world gives people more opportunities to embarrass themselves on dates through phone use and social media. Common mistakes include photographing food, constantly checking phones, and texting too soon after a date. To avoid these pitfalls, Blu e-cigarettes suggests following guidelines such as leaving phones off the table, not posting date updates on Facebook, and avoiding Tinder talk. Other tips include not taking food photos, refraining from checking in on social media, and not bragging about dating app matches.

Ahead of this weekend's Premier League action, Sportsmail provides team news, provisional squads, betting odds, and Opta stats for Tottenham's home game against Aston Villa.

Tottenham:

* Kyle Walker and Hugo Lloris are absent due to injury.
* Jan Vertonghen is a doubt after missing the last match due to illness.
* Harry Kane will again wear the captain's armband.

Provisional squad: Vorm, Friedel, Yedlin, Chiriches, Kaboul, Dier, Vertonghen, Rose, Davies, Bentaleb, Paulinho, Mason, Stambouli, Dembele, Eriksen, Townsend, Lamela, Chadli, Kane, Adebayor, Soldado.

Aston Villa:

* Alan Hutton, Ashley Westwood, Scott Sinclair, and Carles Gil are expected to miss the game due to injury.
* Aly Cissokho might return after training this week.

Odds: Tottenham 4/7, Draw 14/5, Aston Villa 5/1.

Referee: Lee Probert.

Managers: Mauricio Pochettino (Tottenham), Tim Sherwood (Aston Villa).

Head-to-head league record: Tottenham wins 60, draws 34, Aston Villa wins 49.

Key match stats:

* Aston Villa have scored just six goals in their last 12 Premier League matches against Tottenham.
* Tottenham have gained 10 points from losing positions at home this season.
* Aston Villa have gained no points from losing positions away from home in the Premier League this season.
* White Hart Lane is the highest scoring stadium in the Premier League this season (51 goals).
* Christian Benteke has scored seven goals in his last five Premier League appearances.
* Harry Kane has scored six goals in his last four Premier League games at White Hart Lane.

A mother named Jaye Cox made the heartbreaking decision to give birth to her sick baby, Annabelle, at 20 weeks when scans revealed she had a serious form of Spina Bifida. After Annabelle's premature birth, her parents chose to have her buried in a redesigned version of Jaye's wedding dress, made by Angel Gowns, a not-for-profit organization that turns donated wedding gowns into outfits for babies who die too soon. Angel Gowns delivered the dress on the day Annabelle was born, and her family was able to spend time with her in her beautiful gown before she was buried. The organization also provided a replica dress for the family to remember Annabelle by. Angel Gowns currently donates outfits to over 80 hospitals and funeral homes across Australia and accepts wedding dress donations and volunteers at [www.angelgownprogram.com.au](http://www.angelgownprogram.com.au).

A black police constable named Ronnie Lungu has won a race discrimination case against Wiltshire Police, after the force secretly downgraded his internal assessments to make him appear unworthy of promotion due to his race. The employment tribunal found that the force singled out Mr. Lungu, a Zimbabwe-born officer, for unfair treatment, and violated his dignity with derogatory comments based on his skin color. When he raised concerns, they were not taken seriously by his superiors. The tribunal ruled that Wiltshire Police unlawfully discriminated against Mr. Lungu on grounds of race. Mr. Lungu, a father of three, expressed his anger and upset at the unfair treatment and said he still wants to remain with the force, calling for new procedures to tackle discrimination and better education for senior members of staff. Wiltshire Chief Constable Patrick Geenty said the force is "concerned" by the findings and will "learn lessons" from the case. The force has very few black and ethnic minority employees and the judgment raises concerns about how they treated Mr. Lungu. They are considering an appeal of the judgment and will continue to engage with Mr. Lungu and his representatives to provide necessary training and support.

American YouTube user KentuckyFriedIdiot taught his newborn daughter to suck a plastic water bottle, captured in a video watched over 190,000 times. The clip shows him gnawing on a bottle, then prompting his child to follow, with the infant obediently mimicking him. They spend bonding time together with their bottles,

A collection of rare photographs taken by Hugh Owen between 1850 and 1855 captures Bristol at the dawn of photography. The images, which could fetch up to £30,000 at auction, showcase the city's waterfront, city center, and St Mary Redcliffe church, among other landmarks. Many of the buildings pictured have undergone significant changes since the 19th century, particularly High Street, which was heavily bombed during WWII. Some areas, such as St John's Gate at the Church of St John the Baptist, have remained relatively unchanged. The albumen prints were made in the 1870s from original paper negatives and offer a fascinating glimpse into Bristol's history.

Pro-Ukip businessman Harvey Boulter, who previously forced Liam Fox to resign as Defense Secretary, is backing Ukip candidate Jamie Hughes in an attempt to defeat Fox in his Somerset seat. Boulter has already donated £30,000 to Hughes' campaign and is spending another £30,000 to try to defeat Tory candidate Tom Tugendhat in Tonbridge and West Malling, Kent. The vendetta is in response to a High Court judge, Tugendhat's father Sir Michael Tugendhat, who awarded Fox a six-figure sum in damages after Boulter made libellous remarks about him on Sky TV. Boulter admits that his actions may seem like revenge, but he was outraged by the court case outcome. A Tory Party spokesman declined to comment on the matter.

Aston Villa boss Tim Sherwood replied to a letter from 6-year-old Charlie Pye, who had applied for the team's manager position. Sherwood congratulated Charlie on his credentials, despite not getting the job. The youngster had proposed his parents as assistant managers and requested a chocolate bar win bonus, among other things. Sherwood, who beat Charlie to the job, wished the young fan's football club success and offered encouragement in his captain role.

Atletico Madrid defeated Cordoba 2-0, with Antoine Griezmann scoring the opener and Saul Niguez adding a second goal. The victory moved Atletico ahead of Valencia in the battle for La Liga's third automatic Champions League berth, with 62 points from 29 matches. Valencia have 60 points and can reclaim third spot with a win against Villarreal on Sunday. Atletico Madrid remain close behind Real Madrid, who have 64 points, while Barcelona lead with 68 points. Sevilla, in fifth place, have 58 points after defeating Athletic Bilbao 2-0.

An 18-year-old mother-of-one, Abby Swinfield, died after taking M-Cat at a house party in Tamworth. Her family believes her drink was spiked, and police have arrested a 20-year-old girl on suspicion of supplying Class B drugs. Miss Swinfield was rushed to the hospital after the party, where she was placed in a coma, but died a week later of multiple organ failure due to two heart attacks. Her family is devastated by her loss, and her young son keeps asking for his mother. Police are still waiting for the result of a post-mortem but believe Miss Swinfield took Mephedrone, also known as MCat or Meow Meow.

A Tokyo playground has been found to have dangerously high levels of radiation, raising concerns for children's health. Soil under a slide showed radiation readings of up to 480 microsieverts per hour, nearly half the recommended annual limit. Authorities believe the radiation could be coming from something buried under the park. The playground has been fenced off, and a health advice office has been set up for concerned parents. Japan has seen heightened concern over radiation since the 2011 Fukushima disaster. In related news, a drone with a small amount of radiation was found on Japanese Prime Minister Shinzo Abe's office building this week.

Amir Khan believes Kell Brook is calling him out for the "one big payday" he has yet to earn in his career. Brook, who is undefeated, has challenged Khan multiple times, but Khan has declined the fight due to Ramadan, saying that Brook is only interested in the money the fight would bring him. Khan has stated that he will take on Brook within the next 12 months but doesn't consider Brook a big name in boxing, suggesting that Brook needs the fight more than he does.

A Dallas architect, Matt Mooney, has created a stunning 3,700-square-foot, three-bedroom home using 14 shipping containers. Dubbed 'PV14', the home features a 1,400 sq ft roof deck, a 40ft long swimming pool, and a 360-degree view of White Rock Lake and downtown Dallas. The architects aimed to stay true to the shipping container materials, leaving ceilings exposed and using unpainted containers for bedroom doors. Structural integrity was restored with added columns and spray foam insulation. The most striking feature is the two-story, glass-paneled tower reflecting the long, slim pool. The open-floor first level has polished cement matching the shipping containers' overhead steel, while the upstairs levels have maple wood floors. Deep porches protect the home from sunlight, allowing for natural light to filter in. Mooney and his wife Barbara, a retired nurse, are preparing to move into their new home after more than two years of design and construction.

Jordon Ibe is set to sign a new five-year contract with Liverpool by the end of the week, keeping him at Anfield until 2020. The 19-year-old impressed since returning to Liverpool this season, and his impact has led to the new contract agreement. Liverpool also expects to announce Jordan Henderson's new contract this week and is close to finalizing an extension for Martin Skrtel. Talks are ongoing with young defender Jon Flanagan, whose contract expires in June. Additionally, Liverpool has agreed a new three-year shirt sponsorship deal with Standard Chartered worth around £30million a year.

Comedian Rik Mayall, known for his role as Alan B'Stard in the TV series The New Statesman, died last June without leaving a valid will to manage his £1.2 million estate. This could result in a large inheritance tax bill for his family, according to experts. Mayall's failure to leave a will means his estate will be divided according to Government intestacy rules, which take into account his marital status and children. His children could inherit an amount liable for inheritance tax, depending on the value of his chattels or personal belongings. However, the family could seek a deed of variation to split up his estate and reduce any sum left to the children below the tax threshold.

Meanwhile, Rik Mayall's involvement in a 1990s sitcom has an unexpected connection to former UK Prime Minister David Cameron. Writer Laurence Marks, who created the satirical show The New Statesman, lived in the Oxfordshire constituency of Witney, where Cameron would later become MP. Marks, a committed Labour supporter, and his writing partner had become local celebrities due to the success of the show. Although they did not support him, their views on who should contest the seat for the Tories at the 1997 General Election were taken into account. Their advice was followed in 2001 when they supported David Cameron, who went on to become Prime Minister. Marks, a member of the Labour Party, admits that he and his writing partner created the character of Alan B'Stard as someone who understood the inner workings of the Conservative Party. Despite his political views, he considers Cameron a "lovely fellow" and they have remained friends.

The article describes the evacuation of Indian nationals and other foreigners from the war-torn city of Sanaa, Yemen, by Air India. The passengers have experienced the chaos and exhaustion of living in a war zone, and their faces reflect the stress. Air India has been actively evacuating citizens, with India having evacuated around 2,500 people in recent days. Flights are going to Djibouti, a small African nation, with some evacuees fleeing on boats from port cities like Aden. People are leaving behind more than just luggage, with many having to abandon larger items in order to board the plane with only carry-on luggage. The Air India crew provides drinks to the evacuees as if they were on a vacation flight, but many passengers are already fast asleep, exhausted by the process of leaving Yemen. The article highlights the experiences of Damodar Thakur, a professor at Sanaa University, who has lived in the city for 34 years and loved his life there, but is now exhausted and jangled by the shelling and lack of electricity. The evacuation requires coordination between various parties, including the Houthi rebels, the Saudi air force, and Air India, with the Saudis providing a four-hour window for the Air India plane to land and take off from Sanaa.

An Italian priest was sacked after an online lover contacted the church authorities with a dossier alleging sex with prostitutes and explicit gay web chats. The priest allegedly favored sexual role-play involving his lover playing Judas Iscariot, and had previously been involved in orgies with other priests and a Swiss Guard. The diocese confirmed the priest's dismissal but claimed no other prelates were involved.

A new study in the Journal of the American Medical Association (JAMA) has found no link between the MMR vaccine and autism, even among high-risk children with siblings who have autism. The study, which included about 95,000 participants, is the latest in a series of research over the past 15 years that has debunked the myth of a connection between the vaccine and autism.

Despite the growing body of evidence, many parents continue to believe that the MMR vaccine contributes to autism. The study found that children with an older sibling with autism were less likely to be vaccinated, with an MMR vaccination rate of 86% by age five compared to 92% for children with unaffected siblings.

Dr. Anjali Jain, the study's lead researcher, emphasized that the findings show no association between MMR vaccination and increased autism risk among privately insured children, nor any elevated risk for those with older siblings who have autism.

In an accompanying editorial, Dr. Bryan King from the University of Washington and Seattle Children's Hospital reiterated that the data consistently shows no link between MMR and autism development. He stressed that multiple studies have shown no difference in the age of onset, severity, or course of autism between vaccinated and unvaccinated children.

A 12-year-old girl named Jalila was kidnapped by ISIS fighters, beaten, and raped multiple times in a shocking report by Human Rights Watch. The organization found that ISIS fighters kidnapped women and children, forced them to convert to Islam, and raped them repeatedly, sometimes using a lottery system to choose their victims. Children as young as eight have been abducted, raped, and forced into marriage. Survivors who escaped have attempted suicide, and many still feel suicidal due to the trauma. The harrowing accounts of abuse and sexual violence against the Yazidi minority in Iraq may constitute war crimes and possibly crimes against humanity, according to the report. UN investigators have also found evidence of genocide against the Yazidi minority. Survivors need better medical and psychological treatment to cope with the unimaginable trauma they experienced.

Police are searching for Kenneth Stancil, a 20-year-old former student at Wayne Community College in Goldsboro, North Carolina, who allegedly opened fire on campus, killing a male employee at the school's print shop. Law enforcement has described Stancil as a white male, approximately 5'11", with a goatee and a tattoo over his left eye. He is considered armed and extremely dangerous. SWAT teams and police officers responded to the scene after receiving reports of an active shooter, and the college was placed on lockdown. However, police have confirmed that the incident was not a hostage situation and students and teachers have been evacuated.

The new chief executive of Rotherham council may receive up to £40,000 more than the outgoing boss due to the negative publicity from the grooming scandal. The council will offer up to £200,000 to candidates, an increase from the £160,000 previously enjoyed by former chief boss Martin Kimber. The increase is intended to attract candidates despite the council's negative reputation following a report that 1,400 children suffered horrific sexual abuse over a 16-year period. However, some council members are uncomfortable with the idea of offering a higher salary to address the scandal's impact.

Cesc Fabregas will wear a special protective face mask for Chelsea after breaking his nose during a match against Stoke City. The mask, branded with his initial and squad number 'C4', was made by Ortholabsport in Milan, which has also created masks for Fernando Torres, Petr Cech, and Demba Ba. Fabregas traveled to Milan on Tuesday with Chelsea medical director Paco Biosca to have the mask fitted. The midfielder is expected to be ready to play against Queens Park Rangers on Sunday if manager Jose Mourinho selects him. Meanwhile, teammate John Obi Mikel should be ready to return for the Blues at Loftus Road after resuming training with the first-team squad last week. However, Diego Costa is expected to miss at least two weeks of action due to a hamstring problem.

Andros Townsend's wonder strike for England in a friendly against Italy helped him silence his critics, with Paul Merson being one of the loudest. The 23-year-old Tottenham winger has had an up-and-down season, but England manager Roy Hodgson continued to show faith in him. Townsend's goal in Turin was a display of that faith well-rewarded.

A man accused of attempting to murder his wife, who had been cheating on him, wrote her an extraordinary letter from prison asking for his belongings to be prepared for his trial. The wife, who was stabbed multiple times, sobbed in court, taking responsibility for the affair and saying it was all her fault. The couple had been married for ten years and met in 1991. The husband discovered the affair after hiring a private detective and having friends watch his wife. The wife described her husband as passionate and vocally volatile but said he had never been violent towards her before. The case has been adjourned to give the wife time to regain her composure.

The UK will open its first three proton beam therapy centers following the successful treatment of cancer-stricken five-year-old Ashya King. The centers will be available to NHS cancer patients and are scheduled to open in Cardiff, London, and Northumberland by 2017, with the Cardiff center becoming operational by next year. Proton Partners International Ltd is behind the project, which has secured almost £100 million in equity finance. The announcement comes after Ashya received proton beam therapy in Prague and was recently given the all-clear. The treatment aims radiation directly at the tumor, reducing damage to surrounding tissue and minimizing side effects. The UK currently sends patients abroad for proton beam therapy, which costs about £100,000 per patient. The new centers aim to meet the growing demand for treatment, which is expected to reach 1,500 patients by 2017. Each center will provide conventional radiotherapy, chemotherapy, and supportive care in addition to proton beam therapy.

Ambulance bosses in the UK are traveling to Australia to hire paramedics due to a shortage of trained staff in Britain. They recruit paramedics by conducting a series of practical demonstrations, a written exam, and an interview, with successful candidates receiving a job offer the next day. The popularity of these overseas recruitment drives among paramedics is increasing as many in the UK become frustrated with long waiting times at A&E units and the growing number of non-urgent calls. As a result, many are choosing to work as advanced practitioners in A&E, GP surgeries, and call centers. This exodus of paramedics from the UK has led to an understaffing problem in ambulance services, with London Ambulance Service facing a shortage of 340 paramedics. Other British ambulance services are also recruiting from Poland.

Chelsea are turning to the latest fitness technology, partnering with Technogym, to maintain their Premier League title momentum. The team is currently seven points clear with a game in hand, and players like Eden Hazard, Nemanja Matic, and Kurt Zouma are working out at the state-of-the-art Cobham training ground. Chelsea's fitness coach Carlos Lalin praised the partnership, saying Technogym's equipment is essential for elite athletes. Technogym's founder Nerio Alessandri also expressed excitement about the collaboration. Meanwhile, Chelsea has two players nominated for the PFA Player of the Year award, Diego Costa and Eden Hazard, with Hazard being the favorite thanks to his outstanding form.

This article discusses the findings of two studies focused on the cognitive abilities of infants. In one study, 11-month-old babies were shown to have already mastered the fundamentals of physics, as they reacted with surprise to objects that appeared to defy the laws of gravity. When given the opportunity to play with these objects, they attempted to learn more about them by banging or dropping them.

Another study found that infants can understand complex social situations, such as bullying, friendship, and being a bystander, from the age of 13 months. The babies in this study showed stronger reactions to scenarios involving a character who hits others, and they performed better in a learning test involving a ball.

The lead author of this study, Aimee Stahl, suggested that young babies are "remarkably sophisticated thinkers" with rich and sophisticated expectations about the world. According to the study, babies employ their core knowledge about the world to empower new learning.

Another study published last summer found that children who can accurately depict the human form at the age of four are more likely to be brighter in their teenage years. This study, conducted by psychologists at King's College London, involved analyzing drawings of children by more than 15,000 four-year-olds, who were both identical and non-identical twins. The children who drew with more skill were likely to perform better in intelligence tests a decade later.

Manny Pacquiao opted for an outdoor training session at Griffith Park in Los Angeles on Friday, where he ran and shadow boxed ahead of his much-anticipated fight against Floyd Mayweather. The Filipino boxer was joined by fitness enthusiasts and his pet dog, Pacman, as he prepared for the potentially lengthy bout. Pacquiao displayed his skills and strength, including his impressive footwork, while showcasing the colorful mouth guard he will wear during the May 2 Las Vegas showdown. The 36-year-old demonstrated his confidence with the custom mouthpiece, which is labeled "MouthGuards for Champions."

Biso, a cat who has been stuck in a wall at a Cairo train station for five years, has finally been freed. The cat survived thanks to an elderly man named Uncle Abdo, who fed him daily. Animal rights activists helped free Biso after a social media campaign. The feline was discovered to be trapped in the wall by a picture posted on Facebook. Although rescued, the terrified cat escaped before anyone could catch him, and Uncle Abdo is still searching for him inside the station.

At least 35 workers have been killed in Yemen after Saudi Arabian warplanes bombed Shiite rebel positions, targeting reb-controlled army camps in the Red Sea port city of Hodeida and hitting warehouses belonging to a dairy factory. The Houthi rebels returned fire with anti-aircraft guns, and the factory was set ablaze. The airstrikes come as Saudi Arabia hinted at the possibility of a ground invasion in Yemen to force deposed president Ali Abdullah Saleh's departure. The attack on the dairy factory has drawn criticism from human rights groups, as the death toll has risen to 35, with many workers crushed by rubble or burned to death.

Hundreds of morning commuters in Boston faced delays on February 26, 2023, after a truck crashed on an elevated highway over subway and rail tracks. The truck collided with a car on Interstate 93 southbound in the Dorchester neighborhood, causing non-life-threatening injuries to both drivers. To avoid risking train traffic under the overhanging truck, replacement shuttle buses were provided for southbound passengers, leading to long queues. The truck was towed by crane at about 8:30 am, but traffic remained backed up in both directions. The investigation is ongoing, and no charges have been filed yet.

Saracens director of rugby Mark McCall praised his young players after their European loss to Clermont, but stated that the club has no plans to overspend in the competitive post-World Cup transfer market. The club's young English-qualified forwards impressed in the match, and McCall is confident that they will be the mainstay of the club for the next few seasons. Chairman Nigel Wray had advocated for the removal of the salary cap to help Saracens compete in Europe, but McCall emphasized that the club will not rush to sign a high-profile player just for the sake of it.

The decomposing bodies of four men accused of killing 148 people in a Kenyan university attack were paraded in front of a large crowd at a primary school. The bodies were driven around the town in a pickup truck from the mortuary to Garissa Primary School, where hundreds of people gathered to view them. The bodies have been shared on social media, and it is hoped that crowds viewing the corpses might identify them. Survivor Cynthia Cheroitich, 19, who spent two days hiding in a wardrobe and drinking body lotion to survive, was rescued after al-Shabaab gunmen stormed Garissa University College on Thursday. Five suspects have been detained, including three Kenyans of Somali origin and a Tanzanian, who are believed to have coordinated the attack. Al-Shabaab has claimed responsibility for the attack and warned of more to come. Kenyan President Uhuru Kenyatta called on Kenyan Muslim

Arsenal need to make a quick decision on signing Petr Cech this summer, as the Chelsea goalkeeper is likely to leave Stamford Bridge after losing his starting spot to Thibaut Courtois. Cech will discuss his future with manager Jose Mourinho at the end of the season and is expected to confirm his decision to leave Chelsea. Arsenal have long been interested in Cech, but face competition from Liverpool, Paris Saint-Germain, Roma, and Inter Milan. The Gunners may struggle to sign Cech due to Chelsea's high valuation of the goalkeeper and potential resistance to selling him to a Premier League rival. However, Cech is eager to resolve his future as quickly as possible, and moving to Arsenal would significantly strengthen their squad.

Frankie Dettori will focus on the British Flat season this summer, while jockey Gregory Benoist has been signed by Sheik Joaan Al Thani to ride Al Shaqab's horses in France. Thierry Jarnet will continue to ride Treve. Al Shaqab's expanded operation makes it logistically difficult for one jockey to cover both countries. Dettori is happy with the decision, and Benoist is expected to ride well for Al Shaqab. In other news, Richard Hughes-ridden Kool Kompany won the Novae Bloodstock Craven Stakes at Newmarket, while interestingly, Hughes hinted that either the German or French versions of the Guineas might suit the horse best. Sheikh Joaan Al Thani chose not to go with Dettori, and AP McCoy had an unplaced finish at Cheltenham in his final ride there but will continue to ride at Ayr and possibly in the Scottish National.

Lois Lilienstein, co-star of the Canadian preschool show "Sharon, Lois & Bram's Elephant Show," which aired on Nickelodeon in the early 1990s, has died at the age of 78. She died peacefully in Toronto from a rare form of cancer. Lilienstein was part of the singing trio that launched in 1978 and the TV show ran on CBC in Canada from 1984 to 1989 before airing in reruns on Nickelodeon in the US until 1995. The show was known for songs like "Skinnamarink" and "Peanut Butter." Lilienstein left the group in 2000. CBC Television's general manager, programming, Sally Catto, paid tribute to her contribution to Canadian kids' TV.

French freediver Guillaume Néry, known for his extraordinary breath-holding abilities, is seen in a video jumping into Dean's Blue Hole in the Bahamas, the world's second-deepest underwater sinkhole. Although not reaching the bottom, the video is still impressive as he holds his breath for minutes on end. Freediving is a form of underwater diving without scuba gear, and some free divers can hold their breath for more than 20 minutes. The video was filmed by his girlfriend Julie Gautier in 2010.

A suicide bomber on a motorbike killed at least 33 people and injured more than 100 others in Jalalabad, Afghanistan, on Saturday. The attack was claimed by ISIS, marking their first claim in Afghanistan. The attack targeted government workers collecting their pay at the Kabul Bank, and the Taliban has distanced themselves from the violence. The ISIS Wilayat Khorasan statement identified the bomber as Abu Mohammad. The United Nations has condemned the violence, and concerns about ISIS involvement in the region have been growing this year.

Laura Wells, an Australian plus-size model and environmental scientist, has launched an eco-friendly swimwear line made entirely of 100 percent recycled material. The line, designed in collaboration with US brand Swimsuits For All's trend range, SwimSexy, features ocean-inspired coral reef designs and caters to all shapes with sizes ranging from 10 to 24. The collection includes one and two-piece suits with unique features like zippers, criss-cross straps, and plunging V-necklines. Wells hopes to fill a gap in the market for environmentally-friendly, fashion-forward swimwear for curvy girls.

The TrackYourDose app, developed by Germany-based esooka, records personal radiation exposure, including exposure from changes in location and flights. The app, which costs £1.49 ($1.99) for iOS users, uses a mathematical model developed by scientists and meteorologists from the Physikalisch-Technische Bundesanstalt (PTB) in Germany and the University Oulu, Finland. The app accounts for various types of radiation, including neutron radiation produced in the atmosphere, gamma radiation, and cosmic radiation on the ground. It also takes into account medical examinations with ionizing radiation, such as X-rays or CT scans.

Users enter their flight details and the solar activity for the flight, which is inputted using a neutron monitor from the University of Oulu in Finland. A ten-hour flight across the North Atlantic, for instance, results in a radiation exposure of between 50 µSv to 100 µSv. This exposure is significant for airline pilots, who are at risk of deadly skin cancer due to cockpit

Blue Bell Ice Cream has suspended operations at an Oklahoma production facility linked to a foodborne illness that caused the deaths of three people. The company is conducting a thorough examination of the plant to determine the exact cause of contamination. Ten recalled products were from a production line at the company's Texas facility. The now-recalled ice cream, sold in bulk to institutional accounts in 23 states, is not linked to any retail sales. The U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) recommend that consumers and retailers do not eat or sell Blue Bell brand products made at the Oklahoma facility. The recall began after five patients at a Kansas hospital were found to have listeriosis, a life-threatening infection caused by Listeria monocytogenes. The disease primarily affects pregnant women, newborns, older adults, and people with weakened immune systems. The CDC has identified six patients with listeriosis between 2010 and 2014 that was indistinguishable from the contaminated ice cream product. Four of these patients were hospitalized in Texas before developing listeriosis. Blue Bell stated that it will conduct a thorough investigation and make necessary improvements before returning the Oklahoma plant to operation. The company's other two Texas and Alabama plants continue to operate.

Jon Hamm, best known for his role in Mad Men, has been exposed for his alleged involvement in a college hazing incident from his time at the University of Texas at Austin. According to court documents, Hamm allegedly set fire to a pledge and used a claw hammer to drag him by his genitals during a hazing ritual gone wrong in 1990. The documents claim that Hamm was charged with assault but managed to get the charges dismissed before he began his rise to stardom. The incident led to the shutdown of the Sigma Nu fraternity, where Hamm was a member. Despite the dark incident, Hamm's friend claims that it was an isolated event in his life and that he has since made efforts to become a better person. Hamm has recently admitted that playing the complex role of Don Draper has taken its toll on his psyche, and he wants to distance himself from being typecast as a dark, brooding character.

The ongoing dispute over the Falkland Islands between the UK and Argentina has escalated, with Philip Hammond pledging to protect the islands from "Argentinian bullying." This follows Argentinian President Cristina Fernandez de Kirchner's provocative speech and Buenos Aires accusing three British oil firms of working without permission. The UK government has invested £180 million in the Falklands' defenses over the next ten years, and Argentina has threatened legal action against the involved oil companies. The diplomatic tension has been further strained by the summoning of Argentine and UK ambassadors in their respective countries.

Passengers on a Delta Air Lines flight experienced an anxious moment when their plane landed at New York City's LaGuardia Airport and was met by firefighters in full protective suits. The crew had reported an odor of smoke moments after the plane touched down. Emergency workers surrounded the aircraft, and firefighters used a thermal imaging camera to locate a potential heat source while passengers were still on board. Although no smoke was visible, the flight crew informed passengers about the situation and assured them that it was out of an abundance of caution. The plane was taken out of service for inspection and maintenance.

David Luiz, the injured Paris Saint-Germain defender, has taken the phrase "twiddling my hair" literally, as seen in his latest Instagram post. He sports a new hairdo in the style of a man bun. Luiz has suffered a torn hamstring and will be out for at least four weeks, missing both legs of their Champions League quarter-final against Barcelona and potentially eight league matches. His new hairstyle has become a source of amusement for his teammates, especially Lucas Moura, who jokingly said he would let Luiz choose his new nickname. While Luiz's injury is a cause for concern for manager Laurent Blanc, the team will have to move forward without the defender as they pursue Ligue 1 and Champions League titles.

US President Barack Obama has emphasized the importance of diplomacy in dealing with Iran's nuclear program, stating that a comprehensive, long-term deal is the best option. After the conclusion of a framework agreement with Tehran, Iran and six world powers have outlined a landmark deal that would curb Iran's nuclear program and potentially lift economic sanctions. Obama is preparing to address skeptics in the US, who include Republican opponents in Congress and Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu. Critics argue that the deal could legitimize Iran's nuclear program and increase aggression in the region. However, Obama remains confident in the rigorous inspections outlined in the agreement, stating that the deal is "not based on trust, but on unprecedented verification."

A 12-year-old girl battling Leukemia for two years was kicked out of St. Joseph's Middle School in Battle Creek, Michigan, for low attendance and poor academic performance. The school claimed to have made many accommodations for the girl, but none seemed to help her enough. The girl's mother is heartbroken by the decision and believes her daughter's recovery will take time. The family has filed a complaint with the Office of Civil Rights and is awaiting a response.

Passive smoking affects plants, causing them to take up nicotine from contaminated soil and smoke, which may explain high nicotine levels in some spices, herbal teas, and medicinal plants. A study by researchers at the Technical University of Braunschweig, Germany, found that peppermint plants can absorb nicotine from contaminated soils and smoke, and that nicotine concentrations in plants decrease as time progresses, as the nicotine is taken up by the plant's roots and processed in its leaves. This research suggests that the widespread presence of nicotine in various plants may be due to sources other than illegal insecticides. The findings also provide insights into the horizontal transfer of natural products, which could explain the success of farming practices like crop rotation and co-cultivation of vegetables.

Two chameleons engaged in a fierce battle for a female mate, showcasing their ambitions and aggression. The video, captured near the Amber Mountain National Park in Madagascar, featured the males sizing each other up and eventually clashing. The more aggressive chameleon emerged victorious, forcing his rival to retreat following a violent confrontation. The defeated chameleon struggled to escape, eventually crawling across a concrete wall in an attempt to flee. The video ended as both chameleons climbed onto a tree branch and were obscured by leaves.

Scotland youth international Jack Cosgrove has agreed to join Edinburgh next season on a two-year deal. The 20-year-old Worcester Warriors prop, who has been capped nine times for the Dark Blues Under 20s side, will be joining a club that has shown its quality with a strong European Cup campaign. Cosgrove, who knows several Edinburgh players from playing with Scotland under 20, aims to add to the squad's strength with his set-piece game and learn from Alasdair Dickinson. The prop is eager to improve his game and contribute to the club's success.

Aaron Hernandez, the former NFL star convicted of murdering Odin Lloyd, has been sentenced to life in prison without parole. He is no longer known as No. 81 but as prisoner W106228. Hernandez was moved to Cedar Junction state prison in Massachusetts and will be transferred to the maximum security Souza-Baranowski Correctional Center. He is being held separately from other inmates and is on suicide watch.

Hernandez was reportedly hooked on "angel dust," a dangerous hallucinogenic drug that can cause users to experience violent outbursts and paranoia. He is said to have used the drug for at least a year before the murder of Lloyd. Hernandez is described as having been "regularly high" or "out of his mind" on the drug, which he allegedly smoked in marijuana cigarettes known as "killer joints."

Before his arrest, Hernandez lived a luxurious life in a $1.3 million mansion, but his fame and fortune seemed to contribute to his downfall. While little is known about Hernandez's early life, he rose to prominence as a star tight end

Manchester City manager Manuel Pellegrini has revealed that the club's young Academy players are not yet ready to step into the first-team squad, which may lead to players like Jason Denayer being recalled from loan deals. Celtic are keen to retain Denayer, who has impressed while on loan from City this season, but face an uphill battle to do so. Pellegrini's comments suggest that City will need to invest heavily in homegrown talent this summer, including players like Denayer who have spent three formative years at an English club. The return of young City professionals on loan, such as PSV's Karim Rekik and Marcos Lopes with Lille, might also impact Denayer's future at Celtic.

Ander Herrera revealed in a Q&A video that he wears his full name on the back of his Manchester United shirt for superstitious reasons, attributing his successful spell at Athletic Bilbao to it. The midfielder, who joined United for £29million, had a strong debut season at Bilbao in 2011-12, reaching the Copa del Rey and Europa League finals. After a slow start at Old Trafford, Herrera has recently established himself as a key player and has scored seven goals in all competitions this season. He hopes to show more emotion in future triumphs as United aim for silverware.

Despite a heavy defeat at the hands of Bayern Munich in the Champions League quarter-finals, Porto supporters welcomed their team with a hero's reception upon their return to Portugal. Fans mobbed the squad, congratulating them on their run in the tournament, while star striker Jackson Martinez and others looked perplexed by the positive reaction. Coach Julen Lopetegui admitted that Bayern, the eventual winners of the tournament, were the better team. He expressed pride in Porto's performance in the Champions League, which was their first quarter-final appearance since the 2008-09 season.

The BBC has received criticism for creating a computer game called "Syrian Journey" which simulates the experiences of Syrian refugees fleeing their war-torn country. Critics argue that turning the refugee ordeal into a children's game is inappropriate and insensitive. The game allows players to choose a male or female character and attempt to flee Syria via Turkey or Egypt, making difficult decisions along the way. Potential outcomes include drowning in the Mediterranean, being sold to militia groups, or being separated from family members. Middle East expert Chris Walker called the game "tasteless," while Twitter users expressed their outrage. The game, which was published on the BBC website last week, aims to educate audiences about the difficult choices faced by Syrian families daily. The BBC has defended the game, stating that it has received more than a million online hits per week.

Boston Marathon bomber Dzhokar Tsarnaev has received another lifeline from his victims, with Jessica Kensky and Patrick Downes, who lost limbs in the 2013 attack, opposing the death penalty for Tsarnaev. The couple urged others to "overcome the impulse for vengeance" and suggested that life in prison without parole would be a better punishment. This follows a similar appeal from the family of eight-year-old Martin Richard, who was killed in the blast, with his seven-year-old sister, Jane, losing a leg. A jury will decide Tsarnaev's sentencing this week, with options being death or life in prison without parole.

Hamdi Ulukaya, the founder and CEO of Chobani, has settled a lawsuit filed by his ex-wife, Ayse Giray, who claimed half of the $2 billion Greek yogurt empire. The settlement occurred just before a court ruling on whether Giray could be retroactively named a shareholder in Chobani's predecessor company, Euphrates. Although the company was not an issue in their divorce, Giray based her claim on handwritten notes allegedly confirming financial assistance from her family. Chobani settled the lawsuit rather than risk losing $1 billion in assets. Despite this settlement, Ulukaya still faces business challenges, including the possibility of being replaced as CEO due to a 2013 product recall that led to negative EBITDA and mounting losses. Private-equity firm TPG invested $750 million in the company last year to help address these issues.

Diego Costa is targeting Chelsea's crucial clash against Arsenal for his return from a hamstring injury that has sidelined him since the win over Stoke City. He is expected to miss games against Queens Park Rangers and Manchester United but could be available for the key encounter against Arsenal on April 26. Jose Mourinho will not risk Costa's health and may decide against fielding him if the title is virtually secured by then. Depending on the title race, the club may consider giving Costa an extended break until the end of the season to address his hamstring issues. Mourinho hopes to avoid surgery and could use Costa sparingly for the remainder of the season.

The England C team, which has been in existence since 1979, is facing the axe as part of FA chairman Greg Dyke's spending review. Dyke needs to find £30million to fund grassroots football reforms, and the non-league national team is identified as a potential area of saving. The team, managed by Paul Fairclough, is composed of players outside the Football League, aged 23 and under. Some friendly fixtures have come under scrutiny for their elaborate travel. The team has had some success in the past, with wins against Bermuda and Jordan, but failed to qualify for the semi-finals of the International Challenge Trophy this year. Fears about the team's long-term future have increased, and players like George Boyd, who has since switched allegiances to Scotland, and Lee Johnson are among those who have played for the team in the past.

James Haskell, the London Wasps captain, revealed his inner Iron Man in a serious-looking Instagram post, capitalizing on the hype around the new Avengers: Age of Ultron movie. The movie premiered at Westfield London shopping centre, with fans lining up to see the A-list cast, including Robert Downey Jr., Chris Hemsworth, and Scarlett Johansson. Haskell, an England flanker, returned to the Wasps club in 2012 after spells with Stade Francais, Ricoh Black Rams, and Highlanders in New Zealand. Since his return, he has become a key part of the England squad and surpassed the 100 appearances mark for Wasps.

Police are urging witnesses to come forward after a middle-aged woman was filmed harassing a Muslim woman on a Sydney train. Stacey Eden, 23, stood up for the Muslim woman and her partner, recording the incident and defending the couple after the woman allegedly made offensive comments about Islam, beheadings, and the Muslim woman's headscarf. Eden fired back at the woman, stating that the majority of Muslims are not ISIS supporters and that the woman's actions were disrespectful. The Muslim couple confirmed to Eden that they were "very grateful" for her support. The incident comes amid a rise in reported anti-Muslim attacks in Australia, with many calling for bystanders to stand up against racism and religious vilification.

The mother of Odin Lloyd, Ursula Ward, is moving forward with a civil lawsuit against Aaron Hernandez, the man convicted of her son's murder. Ward's lawyer, Douglas Sheff, said Hernandez will be called to testify during the wrongful death suit, and Ward wants to look him in the eye when he testifies. Hernandez was convicted of first-degree murder on April 15 for the June 2013 shooting death of Lloyd. The lawsuit initially named the New England Patriots, but the team was dismissed after agreeing not to release any money to Hernandez. The team had already paid Hernandez more than $9.2 million of his $40 million contract.

Britain has discovered oil in the Falklands, which could escalate tensions with Argentina, which claims the islands as its territory. The discovery was made by British firms Premier Oil, Rockhopper Exploration, and Falkland Oil & Gas. Argentine officials have threatened to prosecute oil companies operating in the area, saying they are acting illegally in Argentine territory. This comes just days after Defense Secretary Michael Fallon warned of a "very live threat" from Argentina. The discovery could increase fears of renewed conflict over the British territory and lead to further claims by Argentina.

A CCTV video captured the brutal attack of a three-legged cat, Freeman, by two dogs in Tarring, West Sussex. The cat was sitting in its front garden when the dogs pounced on it, dragging it onto a neighbor's lawn before tearing it apart. A woman, believed to be the dogs' owner, arrived in a blue car, collected the dogs, and left the cat to die in agony. Police are investigating the incident, and the family of the cat is devastated by the callous act.

A Chinese woman named Zhu Diandian has become an internet sensation after sharing her daily life with her pet pig, Five Flowers. The woman raises Five Flowers, now 187lbs (13st), and shares a bed with her daily. Zhu Diandian's name sounds like "pig" in Mandarin, and her pet pig is dressed, walked, and sleeps with her every day. Despite the weight of the pig, their bond remains strong. The woman's husband is "tolerant" of the relationship, but her pet dog is jealous and peers at the pig through a baby gate. The internet sensation has received a lot of attention and comments on social media, with people discussing the unusual pet and its daily life.
